  Axioms of Probability Definition 1 (PROBABILITY SPACE) A PROBABILITY SPACE has three components:
a sample space \(\Omega\), which is the set of all possible OUTCOMES of the random process modeled by the probability space;
 a family of sets \(\mathcal{F}\) representing the allowable EVENTS, where each set in \(\mathcal{F}\) is a subset of the sample \(\Omega\); and;
 a probability function \(Pr: \mathcal{F} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}\) that satisfies Definition 2
  (Mitzenmacher and Upfal 2017, 2)  Definition 2 (Probability Function) A probability function is any function \(Pr:\mathcal{F}\rightarrow \mathbb{R}\) that satisfies the following conditions:
for any event \(E\), \(0 \le Pr(E) \le 1\);
 \(Pr(\Omega) = 1\);
 for any finite or countably infinite sequence of pairwise mutually disjoint events \(E_1, E_2, E_3, ...,\)
  \[\begin{equation} Pr \left( \bigcup_{i \ge 1}E_i \right) = \sum_{i \ge 1} Pr(E_i). \end{equation}\]
(Mitzenmacher and Upfal 2017, 2)  Mitzenmacher, Michael, and Eli Upfal. 2017. Probability and Computing: Randomization and Probabilistic Techniques in Algorithms and Data Analysis. Kindle. Cambridge, United Kingdom: Cambridge University Press.
